    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-12-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-12-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="468"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d468">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 839.00/1017.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams—Paraphrases.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-12-18">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 18, 1913</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>In harmony with our friendly counsel, the Government has decided to call a
                    special session of Congress for January 4 to consider protests of opposition
                    parties and decide on the validity of the elections in contested instances. As
                    Congress is not controlled by the administration but has an opposition majority,
                    that appears to us a most honorable way of meeting the highly dangerous
                    situation.</p>
                <p>And in view of the admirable attitude of the Government in this matter, we
                    earnestly recommend that the Department give immediate consideration to the
                    financial situation, which is most embarrassing, for the Government is in
                    critical need of ready funds to pay salaries and meet other just obligations. We
                    authorized heavy war expenditures and by our support of blockade reduced customs
                    receipts nearly one half, and hence have a direct responsibility in the matter.
                    Without our assistance neither this nor any succeeding government can hope to
                    survive long. The Government today spontaneously expressed its belief in our
                    fairness and friendship to all parties, and states that its Minister at
                    Washington, Peynado, will be instructed fully to cooperate with the
                    Department.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sullivan</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
